          "body": "The chapter's opening move is deceptively simple: David asks. Not merely 'Should I act?' but 'Where specifically shall I go?' (2:1). This double inquiry — the general and the particular — is the narrator's first and most important characterization of David as king. The contrast with Saul, who notoriously failed to inquire of the Lord (1 Samuel 28:6; 1 Chronicles 10:14), is implicit but unmistakable. God answers the specific question with a specific place: Hebron. David's ascent to Hebron is therefore not strategic calculation — it is covenantal geography, the fulfillment of a divine directive. The men, wives, and households who go with him (2:2-3) make this not a solo political ascent but a community following its king following his God. Chuck Swindoll has noted that the critical difference in David's leadership is not that he was fearless or flawless but that he was fundamentally oriented toward God before oriented toward his circumstances — this opening scene is the paradigm case."
