          "title": "The field of blades — when ritual contest becomes civil war",
          "body": "Abner's proposal at the pool of Gibeon is framed as a military sporting event — 'let the young men arise and hold a contest before us' (2:14). The Hebrew sachaq suggests competitive play or display, as if the battle could be ritualized and contained. It cannot. Twelve fighters on each side seize each other simultaneously and drive their swords into one another's sides — a mutual destruction that resolves nothing and kills twenty-four men (2:15-16). The 'field of the blades,' Helkath-hazzurim, is named immediately (2:16) — the narrator preserves the place-name as a tombstone for the failed logic of controlled violence. The battle then explodes into full-scale engagement (2:17), and Abner's forces are routed. The lesson is not merely military: once the sword is unsheathed between brothers, it does not ask permission to go further than intended. This is the dynamic that the prophets repeatedly identified as Israel's self-destructive pattern — and that David's patience at Hebron was specifically designed to avoid."
